release.name: v0.2.0
release.body:
## What's Changed

Significant updates to repository automation, CI/CD workflows, and configuration files to modernize the project and streamline development processes (https://github.com/andreygrechin/webcolors/pull/21).

**CI/CD Workflow Modernization:**

* Added new GitHub Actions workflows for linting (`.github/workflows/lint.yml`), publishing container images (`.github/workflows/publish.yml`), dependency review, cache cleanup, author assignment, issue/MR closure, and secret scanning, replacing older workflows and enhancing automation and security. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-107e910e9f2ebfb9a741fa10b2aa7100cc1fc4f5f3aca2dfe78b905cbd73c0d2R1-R32) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-551d1fcf87f78cc3bc18a7b332a4dc5d8773a512062df881c5aba28a6f5c48d7R1-R66) [[3]](diffhunk://#diff-9cbc51eceafcef442bca26f982efae9bc095dc325359595ef0ef69b4195f1222R1-R15) [[4]](diffhunk://#diff-8945a3361778b570d0b11fc891f119ef85ed7959a3f49cac6c914a76626bc36eR1-R13) [[5]](diffhunk://#diff-cf2fc1b2155cff28bfdb206f1d53b1da1a8a1d1c3f13f481992fba81865f558aR1-R15) [[6]](diffhunk://#diff-54a6de3722428e960ecf9e7c62854307a1298f0f2c64afce5e77602fb0ad430bR1-R14) [[7]](diffhunk://#diff-2aa7a05eafb406b4c582ed3bd35f2ef3a6fadeaad31372f62a79bd7610e1e453R1-R17)
* Removed legacy workflow files (`.github/workflows/lint.yaml`, `.github/workflows/publish.yaml`) to avoid confusion and ensure only updated workflows are used. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-4b122024a3a28ded65da76a2f1bface1f3a27328374438d1298d25585fe0603bL1-L30) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-e81e13daadd1745de51d8b8d85fce1fcd9be355732b64d60a6b56e18c28388caL1-L78)

**Dockerfile and Build Improvements:**

* Refactored the `Dockerfile` to use Python 3.13 and the `uv` package manager for faster, reproducible builds, multi-stage building, and unprivileged user execution for better security.

**Configuration and Repo Hygiene:**

* Expanded `.dockerignore` to exclude additional development and cache directories, improving build context and security.
* Removed `.gitmodules` and submodule references to simplify repository management.
* Updated `.editorconfig` by removing redundant Makefile rules for consistency.

**GitHub Metadata and Templates:**

* Updated `.github/dependabot.yaml` to reduce update frequency to semiannual and limit open PRs, adding `dependabot` labels for clarity.
* Removed issue templates and configuration file to streamline issue creation and reduce maintenance overhead. (`.github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/config.yml`)
* Replaced the Code of Conduct with a concise, plain-language version for greater accessibility and clarity. (`.github/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md`)

**Full Changelog**: https://github.com/andreygrechin/webcolors/compare/v0.1.21...v0.2.0

issue.body:
From https://github.com/MrXiaoM/SweetMail/issues/51

As you see, Multiverse-Core can not works with my plugin SweetMail in a spigot-based server called `arclight`, which with no `adventure` defaultly.
My plugin SweetMail will adds the four dependencies below into my plugin classloader:
+ `net.kyori:adventure-api:4.22.0`
+ `net.kyori:adventure-platform-bukkit:4.4.0`
+ `net.kyori:adventure-text-serializer-gson:4.22.0`
+ `net.kyori:adventure-text-minimessage:4.22.0`

Multiverse-Core certainly can't find `net/kyori/adventure/text/serializer/plain/PlainTextComponentSerializer` in this situation because my plugin don't need it.

So we should check that is `PlainTextComponentSerializer` exists too.

SonarQube Cloud integrates seamlessly into your GitHub workflow and provides clear guidance for resolving any code quality and security issues detected. The majority of popular languages can be analyzed automatically; no configuration is required!

With [SonarQube Cloud](https://sonarcloud.io/github), you get:

-   Fast, precise static analysis and feedback on your code
    
-   Support for popular languages, frameworks, and IaC tools
    
-   Free analysis for open-source projects and private projects up to max 50k LoC
    
-   Automatic analysis of pull requests and branches with results reported inline
    
-   IDE Support with [SonarQube for IDE](https://www.sonarsource.com/products/sonarlint/) integration
    
-   Quality Gate (added as a GitHub check) acting at two different levels - first, preventing you from merging pull requests that contain issues - and later, helping you to release only clean, safe code
    
-   Sign up for SonarQube free tier and begin scanning your private and public repositories
    

A [GitHub Action](https://github.com/marketplace/actions/sonarcloud-scan) is available in the marketplace to make it easy for you (for projects where automatic analysis isn't available). SonarQube Cloud also integrates smoothly with Jenkins, CircleCI, TravisCI, CirrusCI, and many other tools.

A free tier is available that allows you to explore the benefits of SonarQube Cloud using your public and private repositories. No need to speak with a sales rep or request a license key - get automatic code analysis results on your private projects in minutes! Want to see more examples of SonarCloud in action? You can [explore current Open Source projects in SonarCloud](https://sonarcloud.io/explore/projects?sort=-analysis_date) that are using the [Clean as You Code](https://www.sonarsource.com/solutions/our-unique-approach/) methodology.
